# 9. Defining a linear regression model (glmnet()) using the training data, with Sales as the dependent variable and Quantity and Discount as the independent variables

# Subset the data to only include relevant columns
subset_data <- data %>%
  select(Sales, Quantity, Discount)

# Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(1234)
training_index <- createDataPartition(subset_data$Sales, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
training_data <- subset_data[training_index,]
testing_data <- subset_data[-training_index,]

# Define the model
model <- glmnet(as.matrix(training_data[, -1]), training_data$Sales, alpha = 0.5)

# Train the model
train_preds <- predict(model, newx = as.matrix(training_data[, -1]), s = 0.01)
test_preds <- predict(model, newx = as.matrix(testing_data[, -1]), s = 0.01)

# Calculate the accuracy
train_accuracy <- sqrt(mean((train_preds - training_data$Sales)^2))
test_accuracy <- sqrt(mean((test_preds - testing_data$Sales)^2))

print(paste("Train accuracy:", train_accuracy))
[1] "Train accuracy: 280.111487655242"
print(paste("Test accuracy:", test_accuracy))
[1] "Test accuracy: 688.1274385184"
#An accuracy of 280.11 for the training data and 688.13 for the testing data suggests that the model may be overfitting to the training data, meaning that it is fitting the training data too closely and is not generalizing well to new, unseen data. A difference of this magnitude between the train and test accuracies may indicate that the model is not performing well on the test data. It is important to evaluate the model using various metrics and techniques to ensure that it is truly performing well and to avoid overfitting.

  1. Testing Model
order_quantity <- function(tuned_model, category, subcategory, region, discount, season) {
  
  # Define the range of quantities to test
  max_quantity <- 1000
  quantities <- 1:max_quantity
  
  # Create a data frame with the inputs for each quantity
  input_data <- data.frame(
    Quantity = quantities,
    Discount = discount,
    Season = season,
    Category = category,
    SubCategory = subcategory,
    Region = region
  )
  
  # Predict the sales for each quantity
  sales_predicted <- predict(model, newdata = input_data)
  
  # Find the quantity that maximizes the predicted sales
  max_sales <- max(sales_predicted)
  max_quantity <- quantities[which(sales_predicted == max_sales)[1]]
  
  # Calculate the estimated profit for the optimal quantity
  price <- mean(subset_data$Sales / subset_data$Quantity)
  cost <- price * (1 - discount)
  profit <- (max_sales * (1 - discount) - cost * max_quantity)
  
  # Return the results
  result <- list(
    Quantity = max_quantity,
    PredictedSales = max_sales,
    EstimatedProfit = profit
  )
  return(result)
}

training_index <- createDataPartition(subset_data$Sales, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
training_data <- subset_data[training_index,]
testing_data <- subset_data[-training_index,]

training_data <- training_data %>% rename(SubCategory = `Sub-Category`)
testing_data <- testing_data %>% rename(SubCategory = `Sub-Category`)

# Define the model
model <- rpart(Sales ~ Quantity + Discount + Season + Category + SubCategory + Region, 
               data = training_data,
               method = "anova")

# Plot the decision tree
rpart.plot(model)


# Predict the sales for training and testing data
train_preds <- predict(model, newdata = training_data)
test_preds <- predict(model, newdata = testing_data)

# Calculate the accuracy
train_accuracy <- sqrt(mean((train_preds - training_data$Sales)^2))
test_accuracy <- sqrt(mean((test_preds - testing_data$Sales)^2))

print(paste("Train accuracy:", train_accuracy))

# Function to predict order quantity and estimated profit
order_quantity <- function(model, category, subcategory, region, discount, season) {
  
  # Define the range of quantities to test
  max_quantity <- 1000
  quantities <- 1:max_quantity
  
  # Create a data frame with the inputs for each quantity
  input_data <- data.frame(
    Quantity = quantities,
    Discount = discount,
    Season = season,
    Category = category,
    SubCategory = subcategory,
    Region = region
  )
  
  # Predict the sales for each quantity
  sales_predicted <- predict(model, newdata = input_data)
  
  # Find the quantity that maximizes the predicted sales
  max_sales <- max(sales_predicted)
  max_quantity <- quantities[which(sales_predicted == max_sales)[1]]
  
  # Calculate the estimated profit for the optimal quantity
  price <- mean(subset_data$Sales / subset_data$Quantity)
  cost <- price * (1 - discount)
  profit <- (max_sales * (1 - discount) - cost * max_quantity)
  
  # Return the results
  result <- list(
    Quantity = max_quantity,
    PredictedSales = max_sales,
    EstimatedProfit = profit
  )
  return(result)
}

# Test the function
